              <div class="space-y-3" id="faq-container">
                <div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md">
                  <button
                    type="button"
                    class="w-full flex justify-between items-center px-4 py-3 text-left faq-question"
                  >
                    <span class="font-medium"
                      >What is relativistic mass in simple terms?</span
                    >
                    <span class="text-gray-500">+</span>
                  </button>
                  <div
                    class="px-4 pb-3 hidden faq-answer text-sm text-gray-700"
                  >
                    Relativistic mass is an older way of describing how an
                    object’s resistance to acceleration appears to increase as
                    its speed approaches the speed of light. It is defined as
                    \(m = \gamma m_0\), where \(m_0\) is the rest mass and
                    \(\gamma\) is the Lorentz factor. Today, physicists usually
                    keep mass fixed and instead say that the object’s energy and
                    momentum increase with speed.
                  </div>
                </div>

                <div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md">
                  <button
                    type="button"
                    class="w-full flex justify-between items-center px-4 py-3 text-left faq-question"
                  >
                    <span class="font-medium"
                      >Is relativistic mass “real” or just a mathematical
                      trick?</span
                    >
                    <span class="text-gray-500">+</span>
                  </button>
                  <div
                    class="px-4 pb-3 hidden faq-answer text-sm text-gray-700"
                  >
                    The predictions made using relativistic mass are physically
                    correct, but the concept itself is largely a matter of
                    bookkeeping. You can describe the same physics using
                    invariant mass, energy and momentum without ever mentioning
                    relativistic mass. For clarity and consistency, most modern
                    sources prefer the invariant-mass formulation.
                  </div>
                </div>

                <div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md">
                  <button
                    type="button"
                    class="w-full flex justify-between items-center px-4 py-3 text-left faq-question"
                  >
                    <span class="font-medium"
                      >When is it useful to think in terms of relativistic
                      mass?</span
                    >
                    <span class="text-gray-500">+</span>
                  </button>
                  <div
                    class="px-4 pb-3 hidden faq-answer text-sm text-gray-700"
                  >
                    It can be pedagogically useful when first encountering the
                    idea that “relativistic effects make it harder to accelerate
                    fast-moving objects.” However, for serious work in particle
                    physics, astrophysics or general relativity, it is better to
                    use invariant mass and four-vectors instead of relativistic
                    mass.
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
